te guides, advice literature, and other such instruction for behavior from the early modern period to the present day and discovers how manners do in fact make the nation. Eleven accessibly written essays consider a spectrum of cases, from the geisha party to gay bar cool, executive grooming, and good manners for subway travel. Together, they show that etiquette is much more than fussy rules for behavior. In fact the idiom of manners, packaged in conduct literature, reveals much about gender and class difference, notions of national identity, the dynamics of subversion and conformity, and more. This richly detailed work reveals how manners give meaning to everyday life and extraordinary occasions, and how they can illuminate larger social and cultural transformations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEtiquettezJapan. 0aPower (Social sciences)zJapan. 0aSex rolezJapan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aadvice literature.  aasia scholars.  abehavior guides.  aclass differences.  aconformity.  acultural transformations.  aculture studies.  aearly modern period.  aetiquette guides.  aeveryday life.  agay bars.  ageisha party.  agender differences.  agender norms.  agender studies.  ajapan.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese society.  amodern japan.  anational identity.  anonfiction.  apower dynamics.  aself help guides.  asocial analysis.  asocial etiquette.  asocial history.  asubversion.  asubway travel.1 aAbe, Hideko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBardsley, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBardsley, Jan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell, Gavin James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a